<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><section xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0" xmlns:sch="http://purl.oclc.org/dsdl/schematron" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/xpath-functions" xmlns:tan="tag:textalign.net,2015:ns" xmlns:a="http://relaxng.org/ns/compatibility/annotations/1.0" xmlns:sqf="http://www.schematron-quickfix.com/validator/process" version="5.0"><title>TAN-R-mor elements and attributes summarized</title><section xml:id="element-assert"><title><code>&lt;assert&gt;</code></title><para>The element <code>assert</code> names a pattern that, if found to be false in any <code>&lt;<link linkend="element-m">m</link>&gt;</code> in a dependent TAN-LM file, will return the enclosed message upon validation of the dependent file, along with an error or warning. Modeled loosely on Schematron <code>&lt;<link linkend="element-report">report</link>&gt;</code>.</para><para>Definition: <code>((@<link linkend="attribute-ed-who">ed-who</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-ed-when">ed-when</link>)?, (@<link linkend="attribute-include">include</link> | (@<link linkend="attribute-cert">cert</link>?, @<link linkend="attribute-feature-filter">feature-filter</link>?, (@<link linkend="attribute-code-regex-test">code-regex-test</link> | |@<link linkend="attribute-token-regex-test">token-regex-test</link> | |@<link linkend="attribute-feature-test">feature-test</link> | |@<link linkend="attribute-filter-qty-test">filter-qty-test</link>), text)))</code></para><para>Used by: <code><xref linkend="element-body"/></code></para></section><section xml:id="element-category"><title><code>&lt;category&gt;</code></title><para>The element <code>category</code> creates a set of features that share a common grammatical trait such as gender, number, etc.</para><para>Definition: <code>(@<link linkend="attribute-ed-who">ed-who</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-ed-when">ed-when</link>)?, (@<link linkend="attribute-include">include</link> | (&lt;<link linkend="element-comment">comment</link>&gt;* &amp; ((&lt;<link linkend="element-IRI">IRI</link>&gt;+, (&lt;<link linkend="element-name">name</link>&gt;+, &lt;<link linkend="element-desc">desc</link>&gt;*)), &lt;<link linkend="element-option">option</link>&gt;+)))</code></para><para>Used by: <code><xref linkend="element-body"/></code></para></section><section xml:id="element-feature"><title><code>&lt;feature&gt;</code></title><para>The element <code>feature</code> names, through its IRI + name pattern, a grammatical concept (e.g., plural, subjunctive, 1st person) that characterizes a language.</para><para>Definition: <code>(@<link linkend="attribute-ed-who">ed-who</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-ed-when">ed-when</link>)?, (@<link linkend="attribute-include">include</link> | (@<link linkend="attribute-xmlid">xml:id</link>, (&lt;<link linkend="element-comment">comment</link>&gt;* &amp; (&lt;<link linkend="element-IRI">IRI</link>&gt;+, (&lt;<link linkend="element-name">name</link>&gt;+, &lt;<link linkend="element-desc">desc</link>&gt;*)))))</code></para><para>Used by: <code><xref linkend="element-declarations"/></code></para><caution><itemizedlist><listitem><para>Included features must be written for every language declared by the current file.</para></listitem></itemizedlist></caution><example><title><code>&lt;feature&gt;</code></title><programlisting>   &lt;head&gt;
      &lt;declarations ed-when="2015-03-03" ed-who="kalvesmaki"&gt;
         &lt;for-lang&gt;eng&lt;/for-lang&gt;
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;feature xml:id="quote-cl"&gt;</emphasis>
            &lt;IRI&gt;tag:textalign.net,2015:morphology:option:quotation-mark-closing&lt;/IRI&gt;
            &lt;name&gt;closing quotation mark&lt;/name&gt;
            &lt;desc&gt;Examples: ' ''&lt;/desc&gt;
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;/feature&gt;</emphasis>
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;feature xml:id="dash"&gt;</emphasis>
            &lt;IRI&gt;http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dash&lt;/IRI&gt;
            &lt;name&gt;dash&lt;/name&gt;
            &lt;desc&gt;Examples: --&lt;/desc&gt;
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;/feature&gt;</emphasis>
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;feature xml:id="dollar"&gt;</emphasis>
            &lt;IRI&gt;http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dollar_sign&lt;/IRI&gt;
            &lt;name&gt;dollar&lt;/name&gt;
            &lt;desc&gt;Examples: $ -$ --$ A$ C$ HK$ M$ NZ$ S$ U.S.$ US$&lt;/desc&gt;
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;/feature&gt;</emphasis>
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;feature xml:id="paren-op"&gt;</emphasis>
            &lt;IRI&gt;tag:textalign.net,2015:morphology:option:bracket-opening&lt;/IRI&gt;
            &lt;name&gt;opening bracket&lt;/name&gt;
            &lt;desc&gt;Examples: ( [ {&lt;/desc&gt;
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;/feature&gt;</emphasis>
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;feature xml:id="paren-cl"&gt;</emphasis>
            ...........
         <emphasis role="bold">&lt;/feature&gt;</emphasis>
         ...........
      &lt;/declarations&gt;
   &lt;/head&gt;
</programlisting></example></section><section xml:id="element-option"><title><code>&lt;option&gt;</code></title><para>The element <code>option</code> indicates a way to refer to a feature, supplementing the assigned <code>@<link linkend="attribute-xmlid">xml:id</link></code>. Useful for situations where a code requires a value that is otherwise disallowed by <code>@<link linkend="attribute-xmlid">xml:id</link></code></para><para>Definition: <code>(@<link linkend="attribute-ed-who">ed-who</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-ed-when">ed-when</link>)?, (@<link linkend="attribute-include">include</link> | (@<link linkend="attribute-feature">feature</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-code">code</link>))</code></para><para>Used by: <code><xref linkend="element-body"/></code><code><xref linkend="element-category"/></code></para><example><title><code>&lt;option&gt;</code></title><programlisting>&lt;TAN-R-mor TAN-version="1" id="tag:kalvesmaki.com,2014:tan-r-mor:eng:penn"&gt;
   &lt;body&gt;
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="quote-cl" code="''"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="dash" code="--"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="dollar" code="$"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="paren-op" code="["/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="paren-cl" code="]"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="comma" code=";"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="period" code="."/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="colon" code=":"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="quote-op" code="``"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="PRPSS" code="PRP$"/&gt;</emphasis>
      <emphasis role="bold">&lt;option feature="WPSS" code="WP$"/&gt;</emphasis>
   &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/TAN-R-mor&gt;
</programlisting></example></section><section xml:id="element-report"><title><code>&lt;report&gt;</code></title><para>The element <code>report</code> names a pattern that, if found to be true in any <code>&lt;<link linkend="element-m">m</link>&gt;</code> in a dependent TAN-LM file, will return the enclosed message upon validation of the dependent file, along with an error or warning. Modeled loosely on Schematron <code>&lt;<link linkend="element-report">report</link>&gt;</code>.</para><para>Definition: <code>((@<link linkend="attribute-ed-who">ed-who</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-ed-when">ed-when</link>)?, (@<link linkend="attribute-include">include</link> | (@<link linkend="attribute-cert">cert</link>?, @<link linkend="attribute-feature-filter">feature-filter</link>?, (@<link linkend="attribute-code-regex-test">code-regex-test</link> | |@<link linkend="attribute-token-regex-test">token-regex-test</link> | |@<link linkend="attribute-feature-test">feature-test</link> | |@<link linkend="attribute-filter-qty-test">filter-qty-test</link>), text)))</code></para><para>Used by: <code><xref linkend="element-body"/></code></para></section><section xml:id="element-TAN-R-mor"><title><code>&lt;TAN-R-mor&gt;</code></title><para>The element <code>TAN-R-mor</code> specifies that the TAN file contains definitions for the parts of speech for a language, the codes for those parts, and the rules for combining them. Root element.</para><para>Definition: <code>(@<link linkend="attribute-id">id</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-TAN-version">TAN-version</link>, (@<link linkend="attribute-ed-who">ed-who</link>, @<link linkend="attribute-ed-when">ed-when</link>)?, &lt;<link linkend="element-head">head</link>&gt;, &lt;<link linkend="element-body">body</link>&gt;)</code></para><para>Used by: none</para><example><title><code>&lt;TAN-R-mor&gt;</code></title><programlisting><emphasis role="bold">&lt;TAN-R-mor TAN-version="1" id="tag:kalvesmaki.com,2014:tan-r-mor:eng:penn"&gt;</emphasis>
   &lt;head&gt;
      ...........
   &lt;/head&gt;
   &lt;body&gt;
      ...........
   &lt;/body&gt;
<emphasis role="bold">&lt;/TAN-R-mor&gt;</emphasis>
</programlisting></example></section></section>